05745nam a22005655i 9780822393603DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223936037 a10.1515/97808223936032doi  a(DE-B1597)552131  a(OCoLC)727325951  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3917.B6bB739 2011 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a306.4/8424098122200aBrazilian Popular Music and Citizenship /cChristopher Dunn, Idelber Avelar. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b22 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Music as Practice of Citizenship in Brazil -- tDissonant Voices under a Regime of Order-Unity: Popular Music and Work in the Estado Novo -- tOrpheonic Chant and the Construction of Childhood in Brazilian Elementary Education -- tFarewell to MPB -- tFrom Mr. Citizen to Defective Android: Tom Zé and Citizenship in Brazil -- tRude Poetics of the 1980s: The Politics and Aesthetics of Os Titãs -- t"We Live Daily in Two Countries": Audiotopias of Postdictatorship Brazil -- tSoundtracking Landlessness: Music and Rurality in the Movimento dos Trabalhadores Rurais Sem Terra -- tZhen Brasil's Japanese Brazilian Groove -- tEmbodying the Favela: Representation, Mediation, and Citizenship in the Music of Bezerra da Silva -- tHip-Hop in São Paulo: Identity, Community Formation, and Social Action -- t"Conquistando Espaço": Hip-Hop Occupations of São Paulo -- tFunk Music Made in Brazil: Media and Moral Panic -- tTechnobrega, Forró, Lambadão: The Parallel Music of Brazil -- t"Tradition as Adventure": Black Music, New Afro- Descendant Subjects, and Pluralization of Modernity in Salvador da Bahia -- tModernity, Agency, and Sexuality in the Pagode Baiano -- tCandeal and Carlinhos Brown: Social and Musical Contexts of an Afro-Brazilian Community -- tOf Mud Huts and Modernity: The Performance of Civic Progress at Arcoverde's São João Festival -- tMangue Beat Music and the Coding of Citizenship in Sound -- tWorks Cited -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCovering more than one hundred years of history, this multidisciplinary collection of essays explores the vital connections between popular music and citizenship in Brazil. While popular music has served as an effective resource for communities to stake claims to political, social, and cultural rights in Brazil, it has also been appropriated by the state in its efforts to manage and control a socially, racially, and geographically diverse nation. The question of citizenship has also been a recurrent theme in the work of many of Brazil's most important musicians. These essays explore popular music in relation to national identity, social class, racial formations, community organizing, political protest, and emergent forms of distribution and consumption. Contributors examine the cultural politics of samba in the 1930s, the trajectory of middle-class musical sensibility associated with Música Popular Brasileira (MPB), rock and re-democratization in the 1980s, music and black identity in Bahia, hip hop and community organizing in São Paulo, and the repression of baile funk in Rio in the 1990s. Among other topics, they consider the use of music by the Landless Workers' Movement, the performance of identity by Japanese Brazilian musicians, the mangue beat movement of Recife, and the emergence of new regional styles, such as lambadão and tecnobrega, that circulate outside of conventional distribution channels. Taken together, the essays reveal the important connections between citizenship, national belonging, and Brazilian popular music.Contributors. Idelber Avelar, Christopher Dunn, João Freire Filho, Goli Guerreiro, Micael Herschmann, Ari Lima, Aaron Lorenz, Shanna Lorenz, An